'''John Milne Bramwell''' (1852 &ndash; 1925) was a [[Scotland|Scottish]] physician and author, born at [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]], and educated at the [[University of Edinburgh]].<ref>{{cite journal|title='''BRAMWELL, John Milne'''|journal=Who's Who,|year=1907|volume= 59|pages=p. 205|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=yEcuAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA205}}</ref>

He collected the works of [[James Braid (surgeon)|James Braid]] the founder of [[hypnotism]] and helped to revive and maintain Braid's legacy in Great Britain.  He studied [[hypnotism]] thoroughly, including that employed in [[France]] at [[Paris]] and [[Nancy, France|Nancy]]. He was himself a renowned practitioner of [[hypnotherapy]].

==Publications==
Dr. Bramwell wrote:  
* ''Successful Treatment of Dipsomania, Insomnia, etc., and Various Diseases by Hypnotic Suggestion'' (1890–92)
* ''Hypnotic Anæsthesia'' (1896)
* ''On the Appreciation of Time by Somnambules'' (1896)
* ''[http://ia600809.us.archive.org/22/items/suggestionitspla00bram/suggestionitspla00bram.pdf Suggestion: Its Place in Medicine and Scientific Research]'' (1897)
* ''Hypnotic and Post-hypnotic Appreciation of Time: Secondary and Multiplex Personalities'' (1900)
* ''[http://books.google.com/books?isbn=1425483321 Hypnotism: Its History, Practice, and Theory]'' (1903)
* ''[http://www.archive.org/stream/hypnotismandtre00bramgoog#page/n4/mode/2up  Hypnotism and Treatment by Suggestion]'' (1910)

